# Build the Observer as an Activated Pi Extension

## Question

Convert the observer charter (`dark-wizard/.brain/tasks/observer-loop-charter.svx`)
from a kickoff prompt into an activated pi extension that injects the
observer constitution into the SYSTEM PROMPT (Amendment 3 of the topology
ticket). Study existing extensions (`~/.pi/agent/extensions/` —
memory-capture, herdr-name-sync, herdr-callsign) for the API. Requirements:

- Activation is explicit (flag/env/config), never default — only the
  observer session gets observer identity.
- Charter content sourced from the svx file at session start (file remains
  the editable truth; extension is the injection mechanism).
- Cache-aware: charter injects as a stable prefix; anything dynamic
  (cursor value, date) arrives in tick prompts, not the system prompt.
- Restart story: `observer-tick.sh` gains an ensure-session step — if the
  pane's pi is dead, relaunch `pi` with the extension activated; identity
  comes from the extension, state from the cursor. Include daily session
  rotation (fresh session each morning, cursor carries over).
- Receipts: a tick executed under extension identity with no kickoff
  prompt; a simulated compaction (or long session) showing the charter
  still governs.

## Addendum (Joel, 2026-07-12): headless tool policy

The extension MUST disable interactive/blocking tools for observer sessions —
MCQ/ask-user style prompts, quick-pick dialogs, anything that waits on a
human. A headless daemon that asks a question deadlocks until the next human
visit (the quick-pick modal that swallowed a tick during today's migration is
the receipt). Enumerate pi's interactive tool surface from source/extensions
and turn all of it off under observer identity; when the observer would have
asked, it instead records the question in its tick report and proceeds
conservatively (doubt → sensitive, gaps → report loudly).

## Addendum 2 (Joel, 2026-07-12): override + bespoke agents + specific context

- The extension **OVERRIDES the system prompt**, not appends — the observer's
  constitution is its whole identity, not a footnote under default pi
  instructions.
- **Clear the default pi-subagent registry** for observer sessions and
  register bespoke agents for its actual tasks (e.g. terra-distiller,
  ds4-classifier, completeness-checker) — the observer spawns from its own
  cast, not the general-purpose roster.
- The pi session runs in a **specific context**: pinned cwd, pinned env,
  observer-only config scope — nothing inherited by accident.
- Pairs with [spec-herdr-session-management](./spec-herdr-session-management.svx):
  `herdr session attach observer` is the front door to this session.

## Home (Joel, 2026-07-12)

The extension lives in its own repo: `~/Code/joelhooks/joelclaw-observer`
(joelhooks/joelclaw-observer). Scaffolded with the full spec in AGENTS.md;
build work executes there.

## Addendum 3 (Joel, 2026-07-12): delegate to existing session tooling

`joelclaw sessions` already ships the observer's primitives: `extract`
(bounded window context — IS read_session_window), `chunks` (query +
neighboring raw context), `inspect` (regex transcript surgery), and
especially `signals` (role-aware high-signal user-turn mining by kind:
friction/preference/decision/praise/correction/workflow-pattern/failure/
repair-request/mode-mismatch). v1.1: lib.ts delegates to these CLIs in
never-throw wrappers instead of raw Typesense queries, and `signals`
output seeds the Decisions/Observations sections of epoch pages before
terra distills — pre-mined signal beats cold extraction.

## Addendum 4 (Joel, 2026-07-13): family awareness in the extension

The extension injects FAMILY CONTEXT for every observer-session pane:
role, parent pane id, sibling registry (role → pane id), and pi-intercom
wiring so family members message each other in-band. Registry maintained by
the orchestrator (state file next to the cursor); dispatcher and workers
read it at start and on change. herdr send-keys demotes to wake/lifecycle
only.

## Addendum 5 (Joel, 2026-07-13): no opaque spinners — long work belongs in sub-agents

Joel's UX feedback on the live observer: tool calls "don't provide any
visual feedback of progress/activity, just spins on 'working'" — and long
work "generally belongs in a sub-agent." v1.5 design rule:

1. **Orchestrator tools stay short.** Anything beyond a few seconds of wall
   time must not run inline inside a tool call. distill_window stops
   running nested pi -p inline: it delegates — spawn_worker (v1.4 surface)
   for a visible terra pane per batch (name-synced, ping-waited,
   family-registered), or a pi-subagent from the bespoke roster where pi
   renders subagent activity natively. publish()'s wiki build likewise
   delegates or backgrounds with a progress receipt.
2. **Progress is a first-class output**: whatever the ExtensionAPI offers
   for streaming tool progress/details (check pi-mono source), use it for
   the short tools too — counts as they accumulate, not silence then a
   blob.
3. Acceptance: attach to the observer session during a busy tick and SEE
   the work — distiller panes appearing, working, closing — with the
   orchestrator's own pane never spinning more than seconds.

Sequenced after the dispatcher build (same files in flight).
